<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 26 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- Yemen is, for the first time, to host a conference on
oil and gas Monday and a total of 300 local and foreign companies,
banks and organizations will be present.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Yemeni Minister of Oil and Mineral Resources Muhamed
Al Khadim will inaugurate Sunday the second expansion of Dahab oil
field in Ganna sector on the former borders of pre-union Yemen,
the Arabic Al Hayat reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The expansion project can increase the output by 20,000 to
50,000 barrels per day to enable the total daily production of the
field to reach 400,000 barrels per day.
</P>
<P>
RABAT -- Morocco will import 2,6 million tonnes of grain this
year to offset the shortage between its annual consumption of
about 10 million tonnes and its 7 million tonnes of production.
</P>
<P>
The expected grain imports this year are slightly lower than
those of last year due to the improved harvest of the country.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon's Central Bank governor Riad Salameh
predicted Friday that Lebanese interest rates will be cut in the
near future, the official National News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Salameh made the prediction at a conference on capital flows
and emerging markets organized by the Beirut-based Center for
Emerging Market Studies.
</P>
<P>
"I think that the interest rates are going to fall in the near
future because of the decline in inflation in Lebanon, as
inflation is below 5 percent," he said.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran earned some 600 million dollars from
agricultural exports during the past Iranian year ending March 20,
the official news agency IRNA reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Agricultural products, including fresh and dried fruits, and
vegetables, comprise only 2 percent of the country's total exports,
the agency said.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- The Arab Bank, Jordan's largest bank, has recently
decided to open two more branches in Beirut at the beginning of
next year to expand its network in the country.
</P>
<P>
The bank, which currently has 10 branches in Lebanon, is
involved in offering loans to Lebanon's civil war-gutted hotels
and hospitals as well as electricity and communications projects.
</P>
<P>
The two branches will finance medium- to long-term economic and
infrastructure projects in Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
