<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blocked River in Nepal Flows Over Debris </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 26 (Xinhua) -- The Kali Gandaki River, one
of the biggest in Nepal which was blocked upstream Saturday
morning as a result of a landslide, started flowing over the
debris in the afternoon, the official RSS news agency said.
</P>
<P>
The river, which flows throughout the western development
region of Nepal, was blocked at Myagdi district, and a 200-meter
deep lake had been formed thereafter, RSS said.
</P>
<P>
It said heavy rain began after 02:00 PM (local time) in
Tatopani where the landslide occurred, and about 45 minutes later
the river started flowing over the debris.
</P>
<P>
Residents and offices in the area were being shifted to safer
places, and those living along the river banks had been alerted,
the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Construction materials and equipment for the Kali Gandaki A
hydropower project at Syangja district were being evacuated as
well, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
