<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Bosnian Serb President Advocates Amending Dayton Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Nikola Poplasen, the newly
elected president of the Bosnian Serb Republic, said he advocates
amending the Dayton peace accord to gain more for the Bosnian
Serbs.
</P>
<P>
Poplasen told a Sarajevo-based magazine Friday that his
long-term strategic goal of uniting his republic with the Republic
of Serbia and the Republic of Montenegro, which constitutes
Yugoslavia today, remains unchanged.
</P>
<P>
It may take five, 10 or 20 years to accomplish the goal, he
said, adding the Dayton accord could be amended through agreements
among the three ethnic groups and the two entities in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
As far the accord, brokered by the United States as an
effective measure to end the 1992-1995 Bosnian war, the
president-elect said his Serb Radical Party would like to see its
full implementation.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said, the party would advocate the policies of
opening up and respecting democratic principles.
</P>
<P>
He alleged that Milorad Dodik, currently premier of the Serb
republic, had misinterpreted the Dayton accord, compromising many
of the rights entitled to the Serb entity in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Poplasen defeated Western-backed incumbent president, Biljana
Plavsic, in the September 12-13 election to become the new
president of the Serb Republic for the next four years.
</P>
<P>
Some Western countries have expressed concerns over Poplasen's
presidency. Gelbard, the U.S. envoy who visited Banja Luka, the
capital of the Serb entity, said Thursday that Washington had
"serious questions" about Poplasen's willingness to implement the
Dayton accord. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
