<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Export Turnover Falls Short of Expectation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's export turnover was
up 4.1 percent in the year's first nine months but, if converted
into annual rate, was short of the government's expectation.
</P>
<P>
The nine-month increase, over the same period last year,
prompted the government's trade ministry to believe that it would
be hard to reach the year's export growth target of 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, as reported Saturday by the Vietnam News Agency
(VNA), the country's trade deficit was 1.65 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam sold abroad over 8.6 million tons of crude oil, the
country's top export merchandise in the year's first nine months,
a rise of 21 percent against the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
However, said the report, the price of its exported crude oil
was down 30 to 40 percent compared to the 1997 average. As a
result, the export turnover fell despite the increased volume.
</P>
<P>
In addition, prolonged natural disasters since the late 1997
have brought down the exports of many agricultural products,
including cashew nuts by nine percent, pepper 25 percent and
vegetables and fruits more than 27 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese government has taken measures to boost exports,
such as launching an export award fund and reducing interest rates
for businesses that produce and deal in a number of export items.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
