<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-26 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Developing New Anti-Missile System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 26 (Xinhua) -- An Israeli Defense Ministry
adviser has said that Israel is developing a new defense and
attack system that can destroy missiles after they are launched
from hostile neighbors, Israel Radio reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The adviser, who spoke on condition of anonymity, did not
elaborate on the new system, only saying that the size of the
missile system is similar to that of the Arrow anti-missile
missile, the radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Israel successfully conducted an integrated test of its
"Arrow" missile system in mid-September, which is been developing
with the support of the U.S..
</P>
<P>
But some strategists have warned against being carried away by
the technological success of the test, saying that the system is
limited in many areas.
</P>
<P>
Designed to track and destroy offensive missiles, the "Arrow"
will not be effective enough to protect the country since in an
extended attack, some warheads are likely to get through, critics
say.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a more advanced system is needed as more advanced
offensive missiles are obtained by Israel's bitter rivals Iran,
Iraq and Syria, they said.
</P>
<P>
Israel has said that Syria, who has territorial disputes with
Israel over the Golan Heights, is strengthening its Scud missile
system and developing warheads with nerve gas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
