<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Ruling Parties Move for Stronger Coalition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 26 (Xinhua) -- The ruling parties in Nepal
Saturday decided to form a three-tier coordination committee for
better implementation of the agreement and understanding between
them, the official RSS news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
A meeting of top leaders of the Nepali Congress and the
Communist Party of Nepal (Marxism-Leninism, CPN-ML) decided to
form a central coordination committee comprising top leaders of
the two parties, a ministerial committee comprising ministers and
a four-member committee in all the 75 districts of the country,
RSS said.
</P>
<P>
It said the committees will provide guidelines to the
government for implementation of the agreement and understanding
reached between the two ruling partners.
</P>
<P>
The decision came exactly one month after the CPN-ML joined the
minority government led by the Nepali Congress.
</P>
<P>
In late August, the two partners reached a 25-point agreement
on policies and priorities of the new coalition government.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that as the two partners have different
principles, the committees to be formed may help iron out
potential differences and disputes, thus contributing to a stable
coalition government at least until the next general elections due
by November 1999.
</P>
<P>
For the government, the biggest challenge is infighting between
its partners, as it enjoys a comfortable majority of at least 128
seats in the 205-member Lower House of Parliament, strong enough
to fend off any outside attack. 
</P>
</TEXT>
