<DOCNO> XIE19980927.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ghana to Take Liberia's Former Warlord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Liberia's former warlord
Roosevelt Johnson will travel to Ghana Saturday where he will
stay while the United States and Liberia sort out what should
happen to him, a report from Sierra Leone's capital Freetown
said.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted a commander of the West African
peace-keeping force ECOMOG as saying that Johnson, who arrived
there by helicopter Friday, would travel on a scheduled
commercial flight to Accra, capital of Ghana.
</P>
<P>
Johnson, a major rival of President Charles Taylor during
Liberia's seven-year civil war, was at the center of a six-day
stand-off at the U.S. embassy in Liberian capital Monrovia after
he took refugee there last Saturday in fear of his life.
</P>
<P>
"Johnson will leave under ECOMOG protection this afternoon by
Ghana Airways for Accra," the ECOMOG commander said, "The Ghana
government has agreed to grant him asylum while the United
States and the government of Liberia finally sort out his fate."
</P>
<P>
Taylor, who launched Liberia's civil war in 1989 and finally
won power in 1997 in a multi-party election monitored by ECOMOG,
accused Johnson of treason, murder, rape and kidnaping and had
demanded that he be handed over.
</P>
<P>
Washington said after flying him out to Freetown that he would
be tried in abstention in Monrovia. The report also quoted
diplomats as saying that if found guilty at a trial monitored by
international observers, the understanding was that he would be
returned.
</P>
<P>
Johnson, together with two of his sons, two close aides and
more than 20 supporters, left the U.S. embassy Friday afternoon
in two helicopters piloted by Russians arranged by the ECOMOG,
according to another report from Monrovia.
</P>
<P>
Johnson and his supporters forced their way into the U.S.
embassy on September 19, when they were hunted by Liberian
government troops who attempted to arrest him on treason and
other charges.
</P>
<P>
The government troops rounded up Johnson and his supporters in
their stronghold in central Monrovia on September 18, sparking
off heavy fightings that forced thousands of citizens fleeing
their homes and claimed at least 47 lives, according to the
report.
</P>
<P>
Aid agencies said the loss of life could be as high as 350.
</P>
<P>
At least three of Johnson's supporters were killed and two
American employees of the embassy injured when Liberian forces
shot from outside the embassy, while Johnson was negotiating with
embassy officials for admission.
</P>
<P>
Security had been greatly increased at the U.S. embassy and
most diplomats were evacuated. U.S. military reinforcements were
sent in to help shore up the embassy's defense, machine gun nests
were set up on the roof and diplomats seldom moved without flak
jackets and helmets.
</P>
<P>
The American diplomats, who have seen themselves as living
under siege for a week, were happy to see Johnson go.
</P>
<P>
"I am glad this is over," Deputy Chief of Mission John Bauwan
was quoted by the report as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
