<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Adamu's Funeral Held in Brussels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 26 (Xinhua) -- More than 5,000 people
attended the funeral service held here on Saturday for Semira
Adamu, the Nigerian refugee who died of brain haemorrhage
sustained during forced deportation.
</P>
<P>
The funeral service was held at Brussels' St. Michel cathedral
by those who have lent their sympathy and support to the
20-year-old woman in her effort to stay.
</P>
<P>
Adamu died on Tuesday in a local hospital after losing
consciousness as the result of suffocation.
</P>
<P>
Two Belgian gendarmes used a cushion to muffle Adamu's screams
while escorting her onto a Nigeria-bound flight early that day.
</P>
<P>
The Belgian gendarme on Saturday offered "profound regret and
sincere condolences" to Adamu's family and friends.
</P>
<P>
An investigation was already launched into the death of Adamu
and one of the two gendarmerie involved in Tuesday's incident had
been found to have been disciplined in a similar case previously.
</P>
<P>
Belgian Interior Minister Louis Tobback handed in his
resignation letter but was given 24 hours to ponder on his
decision to resign. He is expected to announce whether to resign
soon.
</P>
<P>
The Belgian cabinet met on Friday to discuss the incident and
declined to accept Tobback's resignation. Belgium has halted the
country's deportation of refugees for the time being.
</P>
<P>
If Tobback's resignation was accepted, it would be the second
time within six months for an interior minister to resign over
errors committed by the gendarmerie.
</P>
<P>
In April this year, Tobback's predecessor resigned after
alleged child rapist and killer Marc Dutroux overwhelmed escorting
gendarmes and escaped from a pre-trial hearing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
