<DOCNO> XIE19980927.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Condemns Military Intervention in DRC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 26 (Xinhua) -- A Ugandan delegation, that
took part in the newly-ended 27th session of the Joint Assembly
regrouping members of Parliament from 71 countries in Brussels,
condemned military intervention in the Democratic Republic of
Congo (DRC) by some African countries.
</P>
<P>
The delegation warned that this intervention will distort the
trend of political events in the DRC, Radio Uganda reported
Saturday evening.
</P>
<P>
It also refuted allegations by the DRC that Uganda invaded the
country, noting that the presence of Ugandan troops in eastern
part of DRC was a result of a mutual agreement reached between
the two governments.
</P>
<P>
On the deepening crisis in Africa's third largest country, the
delegation informed the assembly that armed rebellion is not a
new phenomenon in the country since this is the third major armed
civil conflict since DRC independence.
</P>
<P>
The Tutsi-led rebellions erupted in DRC on August 2 and
quickly spread to the whole country. President Laurent Kabila has
accused Uganda of backing the rebels, a charge Kampala
immediately denied.
</P>
<P>
In mid-August, troops from Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia went
to help Kabila out, turning the tide of war against the rebels.
</P>
<P>
The eight-week conflict drew regional as well as global
attention. The Organization for African Unity and the
international community are making fresh efforts in a bid to
solve the problem through peaceful means. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
