<DOCNO> XIE19980927.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 38 Soldiers to Face Court Martial in Liberia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 26 (Xinhua) -- At least 38 soldiers who
fought alongside supporters of former warlord Roosevelt Johnson
against Liberian government troops last week will face a court
martial, a senior military officer said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Lieutenant General Prince Johnson, the army chief of staff,
was quoted by Panafrican News Agency as saying that the defense
ministry has concluded investigations about the involvement of
the soldiers in the fighting in central Monrovia.
</P>
<P>
Johnson said the accused will be tried by an 11-member board,
headed by Morris Zaza. He did not say when the trial would begin.
</P>
<P>
Liberian government troops rounded up ex-warlord Johnson and
his Krah supporters on September 18, sparking off heavy fightings
that continued into September 19 morning.
</P>
<P>
Roosevelt Johnson, a major rival of President Charles Taylor
during Liberia's seven-year civil war, was accused by the
government of committing treason, murder, rape and kidnaping.
</P>
<P>
After Johnson and his supporters took refugee in the U.S.
embassy, Taylor announced that the former warlord and 21 of his
supporters are being wanted.
</P>
<P>
Aid agencies said the fighting resulted in the loss of 350
lives, but the government put the death toll at 50 to 60. 
</P>
</TEXT>
