<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 15:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sanctions Cause More Deaths in Iraq: Ministry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 27 (Xinhua) -- The mortality rate of Iraq's
children and elderly has risen significantly due to the United
Nations trade embargo, the Health Ministry said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In statistics carried by the Iraqi News Agency, the ministry
said that 6,717 children under the age of five died in August,
bringing the total in the first half of this year to 39,468.
</P>
<P>
The number of deaths of Iraqi elderly above 50 reached 2,157 in
August, sending the figure for the first seven months to 47,994.
</P>
<P>
The ministry accused the eight-year-old, crippling
U.N. economic sanctions of causing the serious death rate of the
Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council imposed the sanctions on Iraq in 1990
after its invasion of Kuwait, barring it from exporting oil, its
main revenue earner. This has led to acute shortage of food and
medicine in the country.
</P>
<P>
The statistics showed that 2,917 children died of diarrhea in
August, compared with 159 in the same period in 1989. Those deaths
caused by pneumonia and respiratory infections rose to 1,191 last
month from 53 nine years earlier.
</P>
<P>
Malnutrition-related deaths among children rose to 2,606 in
August from 90 in the same month in 1989.
</P>
<P>
According to the statistics, a total of 466 people above 50
died of heart diseases and hypertension last August, compared with
81 cases in the same month in 1989.
</P>
<P>
The number of the elderly dying of diabetes increased to 316 in
August, 1998 from 81 nine years earlier, and those who died of
malignant neoplasms went up to 1,375 last month from 335 in the
same month of 1989. 
</P>
</TEXT>
