<HEADLINE> U.S. Attorney General Hospitalized After Faints </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 27 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Attorney General
Janet Reno fainted Sunday morning during a church service and was
hospitalized in good condition.
</P>
<P>
Reno, 60, was to remain overnight in the Georgetown Hospital's
coronary unit for monitoring, said Paul Katz, spokesman for the
Georgetown Medical Center. "She is doing well, her vital signs are
stable," Katz told a news conference outside the hospital.
</P>
<P>
Reno fainted at about 9:45 a.m. EDT, during the service at Full
Gospel AME Church in suburban Clinton, Maryland.
</P>
<P>
Kats said it was just a fainting spell and Reno's condition was
good. A doctor was attending the church service and accompanied
Reno in the ambulance.
</P>
<P>
Reno had a similar fainting spell while attending a conference
in Mexico City in November 1997. Doctors attributed the fainting
to exhaustion and dehydration. 
</P>
