<HEADLINE> CPPCC Chairman Meets Taiwan Buddhists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Li Ruihuan, a member of the
Standing Committee of the Political Bureau of the Central
Committee of the Communist Party of China, met here today with a
Taiwan delegation which has come to take the sariras (bone ashes
of master monks) of Xuan Zang, an ancient Chinese monk, to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Extending a welcome to the visitors, Li, who is also
chairman of the National Committee of the Chinese People's
Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC), called Xuan
Zang's sariras to Taiwan a very significant event, which will
help boost Buddhist and cultural exchanges between compatriots on
both sides of the Taiwan Straits.
</P>
<P>
Xuan Zang's parietal bone sariras is currently housed in the
Linggu Temple in Nanjing, capital of east China's Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
Li congratulated the Taiwanese visitors on a successful
mission.
</P>
<P>
The religious exchange program across the Taiwan Straits is an
important component of cross-straits exchanges, he said, and many
insightful Buddhists in Taiwan have done much for the development
of cross-strait relations in recent years.
</P>
<P>
He said he hoped Buddhists on both sides of the Taiwan Straits
will take part in more meaningful activities and arrive at common
understandings through cultural exchanges to contribute to China's
peaceful reunification.
</P>
<P>
Li said Buddhism has become part of traditional Chinese culture
in its long course of development, and many Buddhist propositions,
such as charity, are in line with the ethical and cultural
progress that China is working toward.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that Buddhists will give full play to the
positive part of Buddhist theology and have them serve social and
cultural progress.  
</P>
</TEXT>
