<HEADLINE> Li Stresses Curbs on Judicial Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Li Peng, China's top
legislator, has called for greater efforts in educating and
disciplining judicial and law enforcement personnel.
</P>
<P>
Li, chairman of the National People's Congress Standing
Committee and member of the Standing Committee of the Political
Bureau of the Chinese Communist Party Central Committee, made his
remarks during an inspection tour to Inner Mongolia Autonomous
Region from September 24 to 27.
</P>
<P>
After hearing reports from the Autonomous Region's Higher
People's Court and the People's Procuratorate yesterday, Li warned
judicial bodies not to take the "educational rectification
campaign" as a temporary move, but to further it by taking
efficient measures to curb judicial corruption.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed the building of a fair, honest and efficient
work force by improving the quality of judicial department
officials.
</P>
<P>
Li spoke highly of the progress made in Baotou, one of the
country's major iron and steel producers, during its anti-drug
campaign, and said Chinese people suffered from drugs in the late
19th century, calling this a lesson that should always be
remembered.
</P>
<P>
He also urged regional governments to make full use of laws to
efficiently battle drug-related crimes and protect people,
especially younger ones.
</P>
<P>
During his inspection of several state-run large-and-medium
enterprises, Li pointed out that redundancy should be avoided in
order to promote enterprise production and improve efficiency.
</P>
<P>
He expressed great concern for the situation of laid-off
workers and said, "Governments at all levels should do their best
to ensure the basics of life for the local unemployed, and at the
same time create more opportunities to help them become
reemployed."
</P>
<P>
This morning, Li held talks with representatives attending the
ongoing fifth plenary meeting of the Standing Committee of the
People's Congress of the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region. He
called for people's congresses at various levels to strengthen
their supervision of work and law enforcement and contribute more
to China's democracy.
</P>
<P>
During his four-day inspection, Li visited a town in the
Xing'an League, which suffered heavy flooding this summer. While
paying a visit to the construction sites, Li encouraged villagers
there to rebuild their homes and restore production under the
leadership of the Party and government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
