<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Monitoring Foreign Exchange and Debt Administration (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 27 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government has
urged the maintenance of currency stability and avoidance of
financial risk in a recent circular.
</P>
<P>
The State Council ordered local administrations to further
monitor foreign exchange and debt, and crack down on exchange
infractions such as the evasion of foreign exchange payment and
black market activities, the circular said.
</P>
<P>
With the development of reform and opening-up, China has
experienced a sound position in international payments and foreign
exchange balance and a rapid increase of foreign currency
reserves, the circular said.
</P>
<P>
However, some localities and businesses have randomly floated
overseas loans without authorization, it said.
</P>
<P>
The State Council ordered a more strict administration of
financial and foreign exchange institutes to prevent the evasion
of foreign exchange payments.
</P>
<P>
The People's Bank and the State Administration of Foreign
Exchange should better supervise foreign exchange dealings in the
banks and institutes which are authorized to engage in such
business.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the circular, the central government will
also standardize foreign trade agent services and strengthen the
administration of the processing trade with overseas enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The SAFE must punish businesses which buy foreign exchange from
banks without documents and letters of credit, or with fake
documents and letters of credit.
</P>
<P>
If enterprises with import and export management rights
are involved in illegal dealings to a total value of more
than one million U.S. dollars, the government will revoke
their import-export permits, and accordingly punish those
responsible for the infractions, the circular said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980927.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Monitoring Foreign Exchange and Debt Administration (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In addition, Customs offices throughout the country are urged to
strengthen their administration on customs declarations and
documents concerning foreign exchange payments.
</P>
<P>
A computerized network covering the entire country between the
Customs and foreign exchange administrations should be
established for more effective management.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, nationwide administrative offices for industry and
commerce should clear out unqualified companies which have no
capital, warehouses or regular offices. Those who evade foreign
exchange payment and engage in arbitrage must be punished
severely, the circular said.
</P>
<P>
Public security departments should investigate the cases of
falsifying documents and letters of credit, and outlaw foreign
exchange black markets, it added.
</P>
<P>
It also urged strict control on the scale of foreign loans
and better administration of foreign exchange in capital accounts.
</P>
<P>
The state will implement uniform supervision of the total
volume and structure of foreign debts.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the state forbids illegal overseas financing. Only
State Council-authorized official bodies have the right to borrow
money from international monetary organizations and foreign
governments. At the same time, governmental departments without
authorization are banned from introducing foreign loans on their
own.
</P>
<P>
State-owned financial institutes must have authorization from
the central bank, the People's Bank of China, before borrowing
money from overseas organizations, the circular said.
</P>
<P>
It also urged standardized guarantees for overseas financing.
Governmental bodies and organizations affiliated with the government
are forbidden to provide financial guarantees for any enterprise.
</P>
<P>
The authorities must strictly control the prepayment of foreign
loans. Buying foreign currencies with the Chinese yuan for prepayment
is strictly forbidden, the circular stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
