<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Decides to Enunciate National Fisheries Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's National Committee
of Fisheries and Shrimp (NCFS) Sunday decided to enunciate a
national policy to transfer the management rights of the country's
water bodies from the land and fisheries and livestock ministries
gradually, to bring about sustainable development of fisheries
resources, the official BSS news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The first meeting of the NCFS, presided over by Prime Minister
Sheikh Hasina, also decided to make arrangements for providing
loans to the fisheries sector like other sectors of agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The meeting decided to set up hatchery zones at southeast and
southwest districts of Cox's Bazar and Satkhira and other specific
areas for the production of shrimp and tiger prawn fries which
would be supplied to different shrimp beds of the country.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister stressed the need for increasing fish
resources with the rise in the country's population to meet the
growing protein need, mentioning that the country can fetch huge
foreign exchange through shrimp cultivation.
</P>
<P>
The lands which do not yield crops could be used for shrimp
culture, she said.
</P>
<P>
She noted that there was mismanagement in the fisheries sector
in the past in the absence of any policy and principles.
</P>
<P>
Necessary measures have to be taken for protecting the fish
fries and the existing laws in this regard have to be strictly
followed, she emphasized.
</P>
<P>
She also called for the culture of pearls, turtles, frogs,
snails, etc., as these have potential markets abroad and are
helpful for maintaining ecological balance.
</P>
<P>
The fisheries sector is an important foreign exchange earner of
the country, which has identified the sector as a thrust. The
government in its fifth five-year plan has allocated a total of
5.861 billion taka (124.7 million U.S. dollars) for the sector,
targeting at 2.075 million tons at the end (2001-2002) of the
five-year plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
