<HEADLINE> AL Urges Arab Backing for Palestinian State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Arab League Secretary-General
Esmat Abdel Meguid Sunday urged Arab countries to throw their full
weight behind the Palestinian stand to declare an independent
Palestinian state, terming it a legal right of the Palestinian
people.
</P>
<P>
"The 1947 U.N. Resolution 181, regarded as the birth
certificate for Israel, has also provided for the establishment of
the state of Palestine," the top Arab diplomat was quoted by the
Middle East News Agency as saying before his departure for New
York to attend the current U.N. General Assembly meetings.
</P>
<P>
He said that the declaration of the Palestinian state would
top the agenda of his talks with U.N. chief Kofi Annan and other
officials.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian National Authority President Yasser Arafat has
vowed to declare the Palestinian state on May 4, 1999, which marks
the deadline for the Oslo interim peace accords.
</P>
<P>
Abdel Meguid called for Arab countries to support the
Palestinian stand at the U.N. and endeavor to consolidate the
stature of the envisaged state.
</P>
<P>
Libya's Lockerbie row with the West as well as Iraq's standoff
with the U.N. will figure out prominently in Abdel Meguid's
discussions in New York.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said Friday that he had the "sacred right" to declare a
state in the West Bank and Gaza strip in May 1999 and asked for
international backing. He will address the 53rd U.N. General
Assembly session on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu warned on Thursday
that such a declaration would lead to a "complete collapse" of
the Mideast peacemaking and that Israel would retaliate.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli negotiations have been languishing
since March 1996. Both sides are haggling over a U.S. proposal on
a 13 percent Israeli West Bank withdrawal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
