<HEADLINE> Egypt, U.S. to Sign Economic Aid Pacts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Agreements will be signed here
next Sunday on the U.S. economic aid program to Egypt, according
to official economic sources here.
</P>
<P>
Minister of State for Planning and International Cooperation
Zafer el-Beshri will sign for Egypt and Ambassador Daniel Kurtzer
for the United States.
</P>
<P>
Around 15 ministers have been invited to attend the signing
ceremony which will be followed by a press conference to be given
by el-Beshri and Kurtzer, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Congress has agreed in principle to offer 775 million
U.S. dollars economic aid to Egypt in the next U.S. fiscal
year. The figure is 40 million dollars lower than the 1998
assistance. The aid will be cut by 5 percent annually for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Congress has, however, approved to keep military aid to Egypt
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
The cut, to be in place starting in October U.S. fiscal year,
is in line with the U.S. policy of cutting foreign assistance.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. foreign aid budget has been including 815 million
dollars for Egypt, and 1.2 billion for Israel, in addition to
the aid earmarked for international organizations. Cairo also gets
1.3 billion dollars in military aid from Washington every year.
</P>
<P>
Egypt and the U.S. have held an array of talks in both Cairo
and Washington since July on establishing a new system of
cooperation that puts emphasis on enhancing economic and trade
cooperation and rescheduling the aid program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
