<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Somali Rights Group Calls for Release of Sportsmen  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Dr. Ismail Jumale Human
Rights Center, the local human rights organization in Mogadishu,
unconditional release of six apprehended sportsmen.
</P>
<P>
The six members from the sports community of Mogadishu were
held by militiamen claiming to be from an Islamic court run by
their leader Muse Sudi Yalahow in the Medina area of Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
Muse Sudi Yalahow is one of those opposing Mogadishu
administration and a rival of Ali Mahdi Mohamed, leader of former
north Mogadishu faction.
</P>
<P>
The sports members from a basketball team in Medina were
captured about 11 days ago after holding a friendly match with
other teams in south Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
A sports fan from the area told the press that the
basketballers are not given enough food or water and are now
being kept in a dark room in Medina district for the sole reason
of their openness in sharing friendly games with other teams
elsewhere in the capital.
</P>
<P>
They are also accused of being "traitors" who played with
other teams supporting the Mogadishu administration.
</P>
<P>
The militiamen holding the six men claimed to be continuing an
investigation regarding their cases.
</P>
<P>
The human rights center has characterized the detention of the
six men as illegal and against the free will of the Somalis with
respect to their movements and desires.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time in the eight years of the civil strife
in Somalia since 1991 that the sports people are targeted by
militiamen for political reasons.
</P>
<P>
Calls and pleas by different groups from the society have
brought about no results. Likewise, attempts by the Olympic
Committee and its various federations in securing their release
also failed.
</P>
<P>
Some of the local papers reported that Muse Sudi Yalahow
himself has opposed the release of the six sportsmen for what
seemed to be political reason. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
