<HEADLINE> Besenyei's Winning Streak Snapped in China Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, eastern Shandong Province, September 27 (Xinhua) --
Hungarian Peter Besenyei's winning streak was snapped when
Nikolai Timofeev of Russia won the third leg of the FAI China Cup
aerobatics grand prix here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Timfeev, the son of a World War II fighter pilot for the
former Soviet Union, raked in 9.778 points to snatch the title,
building up his overall tally to 32, only two points short of
Besenyei's leading 34.
</P>
<P>
Besenyei, who won the first two legs, finished runner-up in
the Jinan leg with 9.696. Another Russian Viktor Tchmal came in
third on 9.619 to bring his overall tally to 24.
</P>
<P>
Timfeev's win was somewhat a fluke. "Peter didn't perform well
in the first round yesterday and I took this chance," said the
elated Russian.
</P>
<P>
In the opinion of Chomono Robert, competition supervisor from
France, Besenyei should have won this leg.
</P>
<P>
"Peter's performance is so fantastic, for me he is the best,"
he said. "But it's up to the judges to decide the results."
</P>
<P>
Robert's view was echoed by aerobatic aircraft designer
Charles Wolff of the United States.
</P>
<P>
"Peter is the best aerobatic pilot in the world. He may lose
some competitons, but the eventual winner will be him, for he is
so creative and excellent," said the American.
</P>
<P>
The next leg of the grand prix will be held from October 2-4
in Tianjin, which is 90 minutes' drive southeast from Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The grand prix, hailed by FAI president Eilif Ness as the
greatest festival of competitive aerobatics ever held, has
attracted all the top 24 finishers of the world championships
held last August.
</P>
<P>
After the Tianjing leg, the contestants will go on making tour
matches and displays in Chinese cities Shijiazhuang, Zhengzhou,
Wuhan and Changsha.
</P>
<P>
The grand prix is scheduled to end on November 2. 
</P>
</TEXT>
