<HEADLINE> Self-Exiled Nigerian Dissident to Return Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Self-exiled Nigerian
dissident, Nobel Prize winner Wole Soyinka is preparing to return
home, Nigerian leader General Abdulsalam Abubakar has said.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar made the announcement in Paris Saturday, where he was
on the last leg of his first major overseas visit, the British
Broadcasting Corporation (BBC) said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar's six-day trip had brought him to Britain and the
United States, during which he had met with British Prime
Minister Tony Blair, U.S. President Bill Clinton and addressed
the 53rd session of the United Nations General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The visit is a remarkable diplomatic achievement as Nigeria is
still under sanctions by the West, including visa ban on all top
government officials.
</P>
<P>
According to a report from New York, Abubakar had a
closed-door meeting with Soyinka at about 7:00 p.m. last Friday
at the New York Palace Hotel.
</P>
<P>
During the one-hour meeting, Abubakar reportedly reassured
Soyinka and his allies abroad that the cost is clear for their
home coming to participate in the new democratization process.
</P>
<P>
Soyinka is returning home following the withdrawal of a
treason charge against him, Abubakar said in Paris.
</P>
<P>
Since his taking office in June, Abubakar has repeatedly
appealed to the country's opposition leaders on self-exile to
return home and join his "all inclusive" democratization program.
</P>
<P>
To prove his sincerity, he has instructed the judiciary
authorities to drop various charges against the dissidents.
</P>
<P>
While in Paris, Abubakar also met with French President
Jacques Chirac, after which he said Chirac had agreed to press
for an early lifting of sanctions against Nigeria, and for urgent
debt relief. 
</P>
</TEXT>
