<HEADLINE> Iran Reiterates Decree on Rushdie Irrevocable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Iran on Sunday reiterated
that the fatwa (religious decree) issued by late Iranian supreme
leader Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini on the life of British writer
Salman Rushdie is irrevocable.
</P>
<P>
"The irrevocability of the late Imam Khomeini's fatwa (on
Rushdie) is a fact," Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman Mahmoud
Mohammadi said to the official news agency IRNA.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi reiterated Iran's
positions on the insulting book the Satanic Verses and its author
(Rushdie) in his statement on Thursday following his meeting with
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook, said Mohammadi.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi said in New York that the Iranian government has no
intention to take any action to threaten Rushdie's life, or to
encourage or assist anyone to do so.
</P>
<P>
However, he stressed that any insult to Islamic values would be
under no circumstances acceptable to the Iranians and Muslims
throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
Kharrazi's statement was taken by some Western media as
Tehran's assurance to drop Khomeini's fatwa on Rushdie.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Iranian mass media said that Kharrazi's remark has
nothing new but a repetition of previous stance of the Iranian
government on the Rushdie issue.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian spokesman also criticized London for allowing
Rushdie to continue to make anti-Iran remarks.
</P>
<P>
While the British foreign secretary has unequivocally stated
that the British government and the European Union countries do
not condone insults against religious sanctities, it is surprising
that Rushdie still continues his offensive remarks, Mohammadi
said.
</P>
<P>
He stated that such offensive remarks would certainly result
in further indignation among the Muslim community.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the improvement of Tehran-London ties, the
spokesman said elevation of diplomatic relations between Iran and
Britain should be assessed in the context of the world
developments and the emerging understanding about the realities of
Iran. 
</P>
</TEXT>
