<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reported Drug Abusers in HK Continue To Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 27 (Xinhua) -- The number of drug abusers
reported to the Central Registry of Drug Abuse (CRDA) of Hong Kong
continued to drop in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
According to a government announcement here Sunday, drug
abusers of all ages dropped by 5.1 percent, while those aged below
21 by a much bigger 15.1 percent, compared with the first half of
1997.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, a total of 10,599 drug abusers
were reported to the CRDA, compared with 11,168 in the same period
last year.
</P>
<P>
Among the reported drug abusers, newly reported abusers
accounted for 1,643, down by 15.4 percent compared with 1,942 in
the first half of 1997, and previously reported abusers totaled
8,956, down by 2.9 percent over 9,226 in the first half of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Drug abusers aged below 21 totaled 1,700 in the first half of
this year, compared with 2,003 in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Commissioner for Narcotics Clarie Lo said she was pleased with
the continuing drop in reported drug abusers, especially that
involving young abusers.
</P>
<P>
"Despite this downward trend, we've not relaxed our anti-drug
efforts. On the other hand, young people remain a major target of
our preventive education and publicity programs," she noted.
</P>
<P>
On preventive education, Lo said the Narcotics Division had
improved the drug education talk for junior secondary students.
The Division was also revamping its talks for senior secondary
students.
</P>
<P>
"All these efforts are aimed at better equipping young people
with the skills to refuse drug offers, to stay away from drugs and
to understand the problems in life cannot be resolved by taking
drugs," she added.
</P>
<P>
Lo said that some publicity activities targeting young people
would take place in the next two months, including an outdoor
radio show at a shopping center, competitions on anti-drug sand
sculpture and cartoon drawing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
