<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No End in Sight to Lesotho Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 27 (Xinhua) -- There seems to be no
end in sight to the current crisis in Lesotho as mutinous Lesotho
soldiers are likely to wage a guerrilla war against foreign
troops, which might spill over into South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The Sunday Independent newspaper quoted a Lesotho opposition
party leader as saying that he feared rebels might launch
cross-border raids in their efforts to sustain their campaign.
</P>
<P>
"We must take this very seriously," Basotho National Party
leader Everestus Sekhonyane was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"They could cross the Caledon river and kill and maim on the
border farms."
</P>
<P>
He added that the opposition groups had the power to rein in
the rebels. "They believe in us and I guarantee in a week or two
we will be able to bring them back."
</P>
<P>
By Saturday afternoon, 400 more South African troops cross
into Lesotho and the South African National Defense Force was
awaiting authorization to sent more soldiers to supplement its
1,000 troops and Botswana's 200, which constitute the Southern
African Development Community (SADC) peace-keeping force.
</P>
<P>
Despite claims by the allied SADC forces that they have the
upper hand over mutinous Lesotho Defense Force (LDF) soldiers,
rebel troops have taken to the hills around the capital of Maseru
and there are fears that they will wage a guerrilla war against
the SADC force.
</P>
<P>
The foreign intervention sparked off an orgy of violence
unprecedented in Lesotho's history. Angry youths also displayed
strong anti-South African sentiments that spread to foreigners
and the media, precipitating evacuations by Maseru residents.
</P>
<P>
The capital's streets were quiet Saturday after two days of
looting earlier this week, and shoot-outs between SADC forces,
armed civilians, snipers and rebels that left at least 60 people,
including nine SADC soldiers, dead and many wounded.
</P>
<P>
But the town has come to a virtual standstill. Most remaining
South African civilians have removed their vehicle number plates
for fear of being targeted. Many have lost their livelihoods and
possessions in the orgy of arson that razed the entire central
business district of Maseru.
</P>
<P>
The town is without food and petrol, its economic
infrastructure has been devastated and damage is estimated at 100
million Rand (17 million U.S. Dollars).
</P>
<P>
South Africa, unable to cope with the deluge of refugees, has
declared three border towns around Lesotho, including Ladybrand,
disaster areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
