<DOCNO> XIE19980927.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand's Current Account Deficit Worsens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, September 27 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand's current
account deficit continues to hover near record levels, according
to figures released by Statistics New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
The balance of payments deficit in the year to June 1988 was
6.6 billion NZ dollars (3.3 billion U.S. dollars) or 6.7 percent
of the gross domestic product (GDP), NZ Government Statistician
Len Cook said in a media release.
</P>
<P>
This was the worst annual figure for the past 13 years ending
June.
</P>
<P>
For the second quarter of this year, the deficit reached 1.7
billion NZ dollars (8.5 billion U.S. dollars), a significant
deterioration from 584 million NZ dollars in the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
The current account, also known as the balance of payments,
measures what New Zealand spends and earns in a year.
</P>
<P>
The government statistician attributed the worsening balance of
 payments to declining number of overseas visitors, slumping
exports and rising imports.
</P>
<P>
The deteriorating balance of payments and the 0.8 percent GDP
contraction in the second quarter confirm that New Zealand is in a
recession.
</P>
<P>
In view of the continued pressure on government account and the
 shrinking economy, Moody's Investor Services, an international
credit rating agency, recently downgraded New Zealand's foreign
currency bonds rating from Aa1 to Aa2.
</P>
<P>
A downgrade means the government and large companies will pay
slightly higher interest rates on money borrowed overseas, and
international investors will be less likely to invest in New
Zealand.
</P>
<P>
A rating downgrade would normally mean a fall in the value of
the NZ dollar. But New Zealand's dollar had already fallen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
