<HEADLINE> World Tourism Day Observed in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 27 (Xinhua) -- The world tourism day was
observed here in New Delhi, capital of India, Sunday with
thousands of people from all walks of tourism industry joining
hands to form a unique human chain amid magnificent hot-ballooning
and cultural shows at the center of the city.
</P>
<P>
The hot air ballooning and kite flying shows besides
performances by bands and cultural troupes from all parts of the
country were highlights of the one-and-a-half hour program.
</P>
<P>
The show of "solidarity" was aimed at highlighting that tourism
touches everybody in one way or other.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, last year an estimated 150
million Indians traveled within the country and spent some 250
billion rupees (6.49 billion U.S. dollars) in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Tourism generates 320 billion rupees (8.31 billion U.S.
dollars) annually, providing 21 million jobs all over the country,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
Reworking the magic of the bygone eras, "Fairy Queen", the
oldest working locomotive in the world, is expected to start from
New Delhi for a six-hour journey to the tiger sanctuary in Sariska
next month.
</P>
<P>
The locomotive, which was launched at the National Rail Museum
here Saturday, will rekindle the romance and nostalgia during its
nine trips planned from October to February. Built in 1855 in the
United Kingdom, "Fairy Queen" is the oldest preserved locomotive
in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
