<DOCNO> XIE19980927.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Promotes Economy Through Reform, Opening-up (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The number of tourists from overseas China received every year
rose by 31.8 times during this period, while the number of the
Chinese residents traveling abroad increased by 250 percent. China
now is the sixth largest international traveler destination in the
world.
</P>
<P>
In order to promote the Chinese economy, the country has
lowered its tariffs on five occasions since 1992, with average
tariff rate dropped to 17 percent from 43.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
China has also stopped subsidizing its foreign trade companies
and adopted a unified, controlled floating exchange rate of its
currency.
</P>
<P>
It has drafted and put into force laws and regulations on
foreign trade, imports, exports, anti-dumping and anti-subsidy
issues.
</P>
<P>
China now has 160,000 companies to conduct foreign trade and do
related businesses, which enjoy the same income tax rates as other
enterprises do.
</P>
<P>
China's foreign trade and attraction of foreign investment have
maintained a sound momentum. In the past two decades, foreign
investment has gone beyond the scope of manufacturing and
construction industries to enter all principal sectors of the
economy, including agriculture, industry, transport and
telecommunications, commercial retail, catering and entertainment,
finance and insurance.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investment now supports 0.5 percent of agriculture, 3.7
percent of transport and telecommunications and 3.1 percent of
retail industry in China.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the mix of export commodities has keep
improving. Manufactured goods now account for 86.9 percent of the
total exports value, as against merely 46.5 percent 20 years
ago. And machinery and electronic products has replaced textiles
as the largest export commodity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980927.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tourism Revenue Increases in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Both the number of foreign
tourists and tourism revenue increased in Zambia in the past
years, Tourism Minister Anoshi Chipawa said here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to mark the World Tourism Day which falls on
today or September 27, he said Zambia made steady progress in
developing its tourism in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that foreign tourists increased to nearly
264,000 in 1996 from about 160,000 in 1995, a 62 percent increase
and last year the number of foreign tourists increased to nearly
341,000, a 29 percent increase over 1996.
</P>
<P>
Tourism revenue also increased from 59.8 million U.S. Dollars
in 1996 to 75.5 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The minister said Zambia is committed to a private-driven
tourism industry as strongly as manifested in the privatization
of almost all accommodation units of the country in the form of
hotels, lodges, camps and sites.
</P>
<P>
Chipawa said his "ministry will continue to cultivate a close
working relationship with private sector in the promotion of a
viable tourism sector in Zambia."
</P>
<P>
He said that over the years tourism has become a major global
industry, providing more jobs than any other industry. Today 80
million people around the world are directly employed by the
tourism industry and another 150 million are indirectly employed
by the tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
The theme for this year's World Tourism Day is public-private
sector partnership: the key to tourism development and promotion.
</P>
</TEXT>
