<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Lions Suffering from Bovine TB: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Lions in the Kruger
National Park, the biggest natural protection zone in South
Africa, are being threatened by an incurable and deadly bovine
tuberculosis, local daily Sunday Times reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In the southern area of the park, roughly 2,500 square
kilometers or one quarter of the park, more than 90 percent of
lions tested are infected with TB, and scientists said most of
them would die.
</P>
<P>
This is an area most favored by tourists for its luxury game
lodges and proximity to Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
"Lions are dying like flies," Deputy Director Johan Krige, of
the Agriculture Department was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Radical action is needed, otherwise the entire lion population
in the park could be wiped out within five to 10 years, Krige
warned.
</P>
<P>
A survey conducted earlier this year showed that in
southeastern corner of the park, there were 67 lions in 1974. In
1995, numbers had dwindled to 25. In the past three years, this
has halved to 12, and scientists in the park said the most likely
cause of death is bovine tuberculosis.
</P>
<P>
The most obvious manifestation of the disease is animals that
become weak and emaciated, they said.
</P>
<P>
Park officials are now facing two options: erecting a massive
fence to cut the park into two, or killing vast numbers of
animals to prevent further infection.
</P>
<P>
Peter Mokaba, deputy tourism minister, said Saturday that the
situation was so serious that South Africa might have to ask for
international help. "The impact on our economy could
devastating," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to scientists, lions have no natural resistance to
TB. They catch it from infected buffalo. But the disease has also
been diagnosed in cheetah, baboon, and kudu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
