<DOCNO> XIE19980927.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Promotes Economy Through Reform, Opening Up (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Chinese economy's dependence
on foreign trade and investment has grown by nearly 300 percent
since it started its reform and opening up to the outside world
some 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
According to sources from the State Statistics Bureau (SSB), in
1997, 36.1 percent of China's gross domestic product (GDP) came
from foreign trade, as compared with 9.8 percent in 1979.
</P>
<P>
China's ranking in world trade has risen from the 32nd in 1978
to the tenth largest trade nation in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Now it has trade links with 228 countries and regions in the
world, with its largest trade market in east Asia, west Europe and
north America.
</P>
<P>
China has, over the past two decades, grown into the second
largest destiny of overseas investment in the world, next to the
United States. During 1979 to 1997, it had drawn in a total of
348.65 billion US dollars of foreign investment and approved
300,000 foreign investment projects in the country. Among the top
500 multinational companies in the world, more than 200 have come
to invest in China.
</P>
<P>
The proportion of overseas investment in the total amount of
fixed asset investment in China has been growing year by year,
registering an increase rate of 14.8 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Industrial output of foreign-funded enterprises made up 12.2
percent of China's total industrial output in 1996, almost
doubling the figure for 1993.
</P>
<P>
The ratio of overseas-funded enterprises to China's imports and
exports value have increased from a negligible figure to 54.6
percent and 41 percent respectively in the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
According to SSB figures, exports now account for 20.3 percent
of GDP and imports 15.8 percent of GDP in China.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in the past two decades, China has grown from the
the world's 41st to 8th largest tourist nation in terms of foreign
currency it earned. The annual foreign exchange revenue of its
tourist industry has exceeded 10 billion US dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
