<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Experts Laud China's Achievements in Glaciology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Some of the world's leading
glaciologists have praised their Chinese counterparts for their
great contributions to glaciology over the past four decades.
</P>
<P>
During the Sixth International Symposium on Antarctic
Glaciology which has just ended here, Dr. Jo Jacka, vice-chairman
of the International Glaciological Society, said that China now
has the edge over other countries in some aspects of glaciological
studies.
</P>
<P>
Xie Zichu, former director of the Lanzhou Institute of
Glaciology and Cryopedology of the Chinese Academy of Sciences
(CAS) and the first Chinese scientist to set foot on the Antarctic
Continent, discovered the different zones for glacial shaping,
which laid the basis for further research on that continent.
</P>
<P>
Qin Dahe, also a research fellow at the institute, located in
Gansu Province, was a member of the first Chinese expedition
to Antarctica.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese experts are focusing on the study of the acme of
Dome A on the Antarctic Continent, which is regarded as very
difficult, Jacka said.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the institute has made great progress in
glaciological studies of the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau, he said.
</P>
<P>
The convention of the international symposium in China, well
attests to the country's achievements in glaciology, J. R. Petit,
a leading French glaciologist, said.
</P>
<P>
Yao Tandong, the institute's deputy director, led an
international research group to retrieve the world's oldest ice
core, which recorded the climate and environmental changes over
the past 10,000 years in Asia.
</P>
<P>
China currently has one of the largest glaciological research
bodies in the world.  
</P>
</TEXT>
