<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germans Go to Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Germany's 60.5 million eligible
voters started to cast their ballots Sunday morning in the
country's last national election of this century which will decide
who will lead Europe's largest nation into the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
The election puts incumbent German Chancellor Helmut Kohl of
the Christian Democratic Union (CDU) party against Gerhard
Schroeder, the chancellor candidate of the main opposition Social
Democratic Party (SPD).
</P>
<P>
It is the third all-German election after Germany's
reunification in 1990. About 3.3 million young voters will cast
their ballots for the first time.
</P>
<P>
Almost all pre-election opinion polls have pointed to a
cliffhanger vote, with Schroeder's SPD only enjoying a marginal
lead over Kohl's conservatives.
</P>
<P>
Polls will be closed at 6 p.m. local time (1600 GMT) with the
first computer projections due to be released shortly afterwards.
However, due to Germany's complex electoral system and the
possible neck-to-neck race, experts said that the first reliable
projections could only be expected after midnight.
</P>
<P>
Technically, the German chancellor is not directly elected. The
voters only elect members of the German Bundestag (lower house of
parliament).
</P>
<P>
Altogether 33 parties are contesting in the race this time, but
only four to five of them are expected to win representation in
the federal parliament.
</P>
<P>
Following the election, the chief candidate of the party with
the most votes will then be chosen as the new chancellor by the
deputies under normal circumstances.
</P>
<P>
There are 656 seats in the Bundestag, half elected by direct
votes from the country's 328 constituencies and half picked by
voters' second ballot which is cast for a list of candidates
provided by parties in the country's 16 federal states.
</P>
<P>
However, more seats could be added if parties won more direct
mandates from the first ballot than from the second one, which
determines the percentage of seats for a party in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
This complex system tends to favor a coalition government,
which is the norm in Germany's post-war history.
</P>
<P>
Kohl's current center-right ruling coalition, consisting of his
CDU, its Bavarian sister party Christian Social Union (CSU) as
well as the junior partner Free Democratic Party (FDP), says that
they would keep the current alliance.
</P>
<P>
On the other side, the leftist SPD is campaigning to come to
power in Bonn, after 16 years in opposition, in alliance with the
ecologist Greens.
</P>
<P>
If neither group could muster a parliamentary majority, as
recent polls indicated, the only option would be a so-called grand
coalition between the two biggest parties, the CDU and the SPD,
with the chancellor post going to the party with the most votes.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder has said that he is willing to lead such a grand
coalition. But Kohl has said repeatedly that he wants no part of
that even when his CDU comes out ahead. That would open the door
to Kohl's preferred successor and CDU's parliamentary leader,
Wolfgang Schaeuble to take over as chancellor.
</P>
<P>
Whoever emerges as Germany's next chancellor, he will be
charged with the task of leading a country that will take over the
rotating presidencies of both the European Union (EU) and the
Group of Seven (G-7) western industrialized nations from January 1
next year and will join 10 other EU countries to launch the single
European currency, the euro, on the same date. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980927.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
