<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Trade Deficit Reaches 1.65 Billion U.S. Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, September 27 (Xinhua) -- During the first nine months
this year, Vietnam's exports increased 4.1 percent to 6.93 billion
U.S. dollars, while imports decreased 0.3 percent from the same
period last year, the Vietnam News Agency reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
During the said period, the country's trade deficit was 1.65
billion U.S. dollars, said the agency in a report.
</P>
<P>
During the nine months, Vietnam sold abroad over 8.6 million
tons of crude oil, the country's top export item, representing a
21 percent rise from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
However, the price of exported crude oil dropped by between 30
percent to 40 percent compared to 1997's average. As a result, the
value of oil exports fell despite increased quantity.
</P>
<P>
Exports of many agricultural products also dropped because of
prolonged natural calamities since late 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Trade Ministry said that it found it difficult to reach
this year's export growth target of 10 percent, which had been
revised down from the previous 24 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese government has taken measures to boost exports,
such as setting up an export award fund and reducing interest
rates for export-oriented businesses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
