<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Bank Backs Attack on U.S. Embassy: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 27 (Xinhua) -- A Dar es Salaam-based
bank has allegedly played an important role in financing
terrorists who bombed the United States embassy in Tanzania,
local newspaper Sunday Observer revealed.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Ministry of Home Affairs sources as saying
that the Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI) agents and police
in Tanzania are probing the bank, which is said to have received
big sum of money from abroad for payment to suspects before the
August 7 bomb blast.
</P>
<P>
The blast, caused by a bomb planted under a water tanker,
killed 11 people and leaving 74 others injured. Two suspects in
connection with the incident have been arraigned before the
Kisutu Resident's Magistrate Court in Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
The payments were either in cash or by checks, and
investigators have intercepted several check leaves and are
examining them, according to the paper, which did not disclose the
name of the bank.
</P>
<P>
The bank will be closed down and people involved will be
charged for murder if the allegations are proven, it said.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary investigations have also shown that the bank was
used to deposit large amount of money for a sister bank in the
Kenyan capital of Nairobi, where a similar bombing killed more
than 250 people and injured over 5,000 others. 
</P>
