<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Griffith Joyner Honored as a Faithful Olympic Winner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Florence Griffith Joyner
was remembered as a great Olympic champion Saturday at a two-hour
funeral at Saddleback Community Church in California, the United
States.
</P>
<P>
With an Olympic flag haning behind her casket, the world
fastest female sprinter in history who set 200 meters world
records in the 1988 Seoul Olympics, was honored as ran a race
faithfully won.
</P>
<P>
All the attendents showed a mix of affection and anger over
accusations that Griffith Joyner's records were aided by banned
drugs.
</P>
<P>
"She stopped by to tell you all those jealous, venomous words
can't harm me no more," her former coach Bob Kersee shouted from
a podium above Griffith Joyner's coffin.
</P>
<P>
More than 1,500 mourner, including Olympians Bruce Jenner,
Gail Devers, Kevin Young, Willie Gault, Johnny Gray were among
those at the funeral service.
</P>
<P>
Griffith Joyner, who won three gold medals in 1988 Olympics,
denied using performance-enhancing drugs and never failed a drug
test. Her sudden death at age 38 brought rumors out about
possible drug use. The case of death has not been determined.
</P>
<P>
"I've heard a whole lot of bad things, but I don't hear too
many people saying what they've done wrong, what's hindering
their performance," said Kersee, whose wife, Olympic heptathlon
gold medalist Jackie Joyner-Kersee, is the brother of Al Joyner,
Griffith Joyner's husband.
</P>
<P>
Kersee told Mary Joyner, the 7-year-old daughter of Griffith
Joyner "Mary, your momma wants you to know that those tarnishing,
poisonous lies can't hurt her no more. So you don't have to worry
about that venomous, deadly scorpion sting of the reporters. It
don't hurt her no more. See God is protecting her. See God is her
coach now."
</P>
<P>
Al Joyner addressed his wife's casket with his voice cracking
and tears in his eyes.
</P>
<P>
"I keep asking myself why did this happen," he said. "One
thing about Florence Griffith Joyner that not everybody saw was
she gave unconditional love. She was my dream. I stayed focused
on her for seven years until she looked my way."
</P>
<P>
Joyner also asked his daughter Mary to sing a song to her late
mother. People gave a standing ovation when the girl sang "When
Wind Blew on Me."
</P>
<P>
William Hybl, president of the U.S. Olympic Committee, and
Anita De Frantz, vice president of the International Olympic
Committee, hailed Griffith Joyner's kindness and will to
succeed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
