<HEADLINE> Dhaka Vows to Help Boost Software Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's cabinet ministers
Saturday assured software entrepreneurs of their concerted efforts
to boost the software industry and help them penetrate the global
market, media reports here said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The ministers gave the assurance to the software entrepreneurs
at a seminar on "How to Enter the Software Export Market" held in
Dhaka.
</P>
<P>
The computer and software industry would have a significant
role in the national economy, Finance Minister S.A.M.S. Kabria
said, calling on all concerned to make the use of computer popular
among school students so that they can enter the software business
in future.
</P>
<P>
He urged bankers to provide financial assistance, like
operating and venture capital to the entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
"A high powered committee of experts from both government and
the private sector has been formed and a set of recommendations
are already in place," he told the seminar, adding that a
monitoring committee has been set up to closely supervise the
implementation of those recommendations.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry's decision on duty-free imports of
computer hardware and software was highly appreciated at the
seminar.
</P>
<P>
Commerce and Industry Minister Tofael Ahmed said the government
would provide the information technology (IT) entrepreneurs a
suitable place to develop an IT village near the capital city of
Dhaka.
</P>
<P>
He said that he would gradually implement all of the 45
recommendations made by a task force on the development of the
software industry in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The target for software exports for the next five years has to
be revised from 8.2 billion U.S. dollars to 10 billion dollars, he
said. 
</P>
