<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, September 26 (Xinhua) -- The termination of
negotiations and failure to establish a multinational
anti-narcotics center (MCC) in Panama was regarded as a victory of
the Panamanian people, the local press reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
National Movement for Sovereignty Defense leader Genaro Lopez
said that "this news brightens our day," since finally his effort
against continued United States military presence in Panama after
the year 2000 was not in vain.
</P>
<P>
"The MCC failure has been a victory for the Panamanian people,"
said the leader of the movement, which is made up by some 50
labor, farmers and students unions.
</P>
<P>
Former Panamanian president Jorge Illueca said that the
Panamanian government had no other choice but to declare the MCC
negotiations terminated on Thursday, because the United States
intended to turn Panama into a "big military base."
</P>
<P>
The Panama Canal Torrijos-Carter treaties singed in 1997
require the departure of American soldiers by December 31, 1999,
when control over the waterway reverts to Panama.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the two countries have sought agreement on
establishing the MCC in which military personnel from the U.S.
and many hemispheric countries would take part. 
</P>
