<HEADLINE> Nepali PM Stresses Development of Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Nepali Prime Minister
Girija Prasad Koirala said that the government accords special
priority to tourism since it is only through the proper
development of this sector that Nepal can gain more benefits.
</P>
<P>
In a message on the occasion of the 19th World Tourism Day
which falls on Sunday, Koirala said that Nepal is rich in natural
heritage, and the Visit Nepal Year'98 is now in operation with a
view to promoting tourism professionally before stepping into the
21st century by expanding tourism activities across the country.
</P>
<P>
The tourism day is being celebrated in Nepal throughout the
whole week under the slogan of "Public-Private Partnership: the
Key to Tourism Development and Promotion," the government-owned
The Rising Nepal daily reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
By launching the Visit Nepal Year in January this year, Nepal
aims to create public awareness toward tourism, one of the major
foreign exchange earners for the country, develop infrastructure,
standardize services and increase the tourist arrivals to 500,000
from an average of 300,000 in the past years.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that tourist arrivals by air in the
country reached some 205,600 during the first seven months of this
year, up 9.7 percent over the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
As the Austrian Airlines and the Transavia Airlines of the
Netherlands began last Thursday regular flights to Kathmandu, it
is expected that more European tourists will be brought in.
</P>
