<HEADLINE> Italian President Optimistic About Avoiding Government Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Italian President Oscar Luigi
Scalfaro said in Pescara Saturday that there were reasons to hope
that a government crisis over the 1999 budget could be averted.
</P>
<P>
After a speech which reiterated recent calls for political
sacrifices for the "common good," Scalfaro was asked how he viewed
the current stand-off between the government and its some time
ally Communist Refoundation.
</P>
<P>
"There are no certainties, but a motivated, serious and serene
optimism," he said. "When I make a call, if I didn't have any hope,
I wouldn't make it at all," he added when asked how hopeful he was
of a solution being found.
</P>
<P>
Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi Friday unveiled a 1999
budget that went much farther than expected in allotting cash for
social policies, a move he said was designed to woo the left ally
back into the fold.
</P>
<P>
"I wonder how Communist Refoundation can still justify not
voting for this budget?" the prime minister told reporters.
</P>
<P>
But the 14.7 trillion lire (8.6 billion U.S. dollars) package,
containing an extra 1.2 trillion (706 million dollars) for the
worse-off, still failed to win the support of Fausto Bertinotti,
leader of the Communist Refoundation.
</P>
<P>
Italian Communist Refoundation's final decision on the budget
bill is expected to come at a party's conference on October 3 and
4. 
</P>
</TEXT>
