<DOCNO> XIE19980927.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Plans to Re-organize Foreign-funded Retail Ventures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 27 (Xinhua) -- China is expected to issue a
special regulation governing the opening of the retail sector
after a reorganization of 277 Sino-foreign commercial joint
ventures, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
He Ju, director general of the foreign investment
administration department of the State Development Planning
Commission (SDPC), was quoted as saying that China is to open up
its retail sector gradually, allowing pilot joint ventures in more
cities and lower market access restrictions for foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
But he said this will not take place until the completion of the
reorganization of 277 foreign-funded commercial joint ventures.
</P>
<P>
Only the State Council is empowered to approve pilot joint
ventures, but some local governments have overstepped their
authority by approving a number of such enterprises, according to
the official.
</P>
<P>
Given the surfeit of commercial firms in urban areas, this has
worsened the commercial environment and led to unfair competition
in big cities, he said.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that the re-organization drive started last
year and is scheduled to finish by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Those firms subject to the reorganization will be allowed to
continue operations if promised foreign investment has
materialized and the firms have sound management, pass annual
inspections and do not engage in wholesale business, he noted.
</P>
<P>
However, he added, Chinese partners should hold at least 50
percent of the shares in retail joint ventures. The share-holding
requirement can be as low as 40 percent in the country's central
and western regions.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in chain stores or warehouse-style stores, Chinese
partners must hold a majority of the joint venture shares. The
Sino-foreign partnership can be as long as 30 years in coastal
regions and 40 years in central and western regions, the
director-general said.
</P>
<P>
Regulations on the opening up of the retail sector were
announced in 1992, when the government decided to allow pilot
commercial joint ventures in 12 cities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980927.0122 </DOCNO>
