<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Petrol Consumption Tax to Replace Road Fee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 27 (Xinhua) -- China is expected to take the
first step in its drive to turn administrative fees into tax items
in early 1999, when a petrol and diesel consumption tax will
replace the traditional road maintenance fee, according to a key
member of a government think-tank under the Ministry of Finance.
</P>
<P>
The tax will be added at the pump, today's China Daily quoted
Jia Kang, deputy director of the ministry's Institute for Fiscal
Science, as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, non-government toll highways are likely to be
permitted to continue collecting tolls. This will enable investors
to get their proper returns, he said.
</P>
<P>
The road maintenance fee is charged by communications
authorities on every motor vehicle in service.
</P>
<P>
The fee, which is supposed to be used to maintain roads built
by the government, is among thousands of charges levied by
governments at different levels. The levies constitute the prime
source of so-called "off-budget" revenues.
</P>
<P>
The gasoline tax represents part of the government's ongoing
efforts to stamp out illegal charges and fiscalize the necessary
ones for better management of its revenues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980927.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southeast Europe to Establish Peace-keeping Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Seven southeast European
countries agreed Saturday to establish a peace-keeping force for
southeast Europe, the Macedonia News Agency reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Defense Ministers of Macedonia, Albania, Bulgaria, Greece,
Italy, Romania and Turkey signed an agreement Saturday in Skoplje,
capital of Macedonia, to establish the peace-keeping force at
their third annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, the peace-keeping force will have
11 mechanized companies and three infantry companies with 3,000
to 4,000 troops from the seven countries.
</P>
<P>
But the location of the headquarters has not been decided due
to differences of opinions.
</P>
<P>
The main task of the force is to take part in peace-keeping
actions of North Atlantic Treaty Organization, the West European
Union and the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Macedonia will send about 150 troops to join the force, the
news agency said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
