<DOCNO> XIE19980927.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Valley Attracts Scientists to Rare Plant Species </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, September 27 (Xinhua) -- Wild Flower Valley, an outlying
mountainous place in central China's Hubei Province, is rarely
known to outsiders, but in recent years it has become increasingly
attractive to scientists.
</P>
<P>
In the early 1990s, Chinese scientists discovered more than 20
rare plant species including wild wintersweet, wild peonies and
Chinese yews in this Baokang County valley in western Hubei.
</P>
<P>
The 20-km-long valley is part of the Jingshan Mountain Range,
which was formed in remote geological ages and retain many of its
ancient features.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the natural landscape has remained virtually
unchanged for millions of years, with a great many rare plant
species preserved, making Baokang a "biological gene bank'"
</P>
<P>
Almost half of the wild peony species so far found in the world
can be found here, and there are more than 100,000 wild peony
trees in the area, covering about 167 hectares.
</P>
<P>
There are 11 varieties of Chinese yews in the world, five in
all of China and two in Baokang. A total of 50,000 Chinese yews
are in the valley covering an area of 2,000 hectares. The Chinese
yew is used as a herbal medicine in helping treat tumors,
including a few cancers like lung cancer and ovary cancer, and its
extract can sell as much as for some one million U.S. dollars per
kilogram.
</P>
<P>
The valley is also called the "kingdom of wintersweet" by the
local people. There are 800 hectares of wild wintersweet in the
valley whose heights range from 4 to 10 meters, much
taller than scientists had ever seen before.
</P>
<P>
The largest one is 110 years old, 13.5 meters high and
0.27 meters around.
</P>
<P>
In addition, some 100 varieties of rare wildlife live in the
valley including antelopes, masked civets and wild boars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
