<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 01:00 GMT, September 27 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM -- Sudan has submitted a memorandum to the
U.N. Security Council to complain about the U.S. recent threats of
new strikes against Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of Sudanese Foreign Relations Ministry Hassan Abdin
told reporters Saturday that the memorandum called on the Security
Council to use its authority to prevent the U.S. from persistence
in violating the U.N. Charter. (Sudan-Memorandum)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BONN -- Tense atmosphere hung overall in Germany on Saturday as
voters prepared for the last national election of this century
which will decide who will lead Europe's largest nation into the
21st century.
</P>
<P>
The election will put the incumbent German chancellor Helmut
Kohl of the Christian Democratic Union (CDU) party against a
political fresh face, Gerhard Schroeder, from the main opposition
Social Democratic Party (SPD). (Germany-Elections)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ZAGREB -- Nikola Poplasen, the newly elected president of the
Bosnian Serb Republic, said he advocates amending the Dayton peace
accord to gain more for the Bosnian Serbs.
</P>
<P>
Poplasen told a Sarajevo-based magazine Friday that his
long-term strategic goal of uniting his republic with the Republic
of Serbia and the Republic of Montenegro, which constitutes
Yugoslavia today, remains unchanged. (Bosnia-Serb Election)
</P>
