<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Braces for General Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Tense atmosphere hung overall in
Germany on Saturday as voters prepared for the last national
election of this century which will decide who will lead Europe's
largest nation into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The election will put the incumbent German chancellor Helmut
Kohl of the Christian Democratic Union (CDU) party against a
political fresh face, Gerhard Schroeder, from the main opposition
Social Democratic Party (SPD).
</P>
<P>
Almost all opinion polls have pointed to a cliffhanger vote
with Schroeder, premier of Germany's Lower Saxony state and SPD's
chancellor candidate, only enjoying a marginal lead over Kohl, who
has been German chancellor since 1982.
</P>
<P>
Technically, the German chancellor is not directly elected. The
country's 60.5 million eligible voters will on Sunday elect
members of the German Bundestag (lower house of parliament).
</P>
<P>
Following the election, the chief candidate of the party with
most votes will then be chosen as the new chancellor by the
deputies under normal circumstances.
</P>
<P>
There are 656 seats in the Bundestag, half elected by direct
votes from the country's 328 constituencies and half picked by
voters' second ballot which is cast for a list of candidates
provided by parties in the country's 16 federal states.
</P>
<P>
However, more seats could be added if parties won more direct
mandates from the first ballot than from the second one, which
determines the percentage of seats for a party in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
This complex system tends to favor a coalition government as
was the case in most of Germany's post-war history.
</P>
<P>
Kohl's current center-right ruling coalition, consisting of his
CDU, its Bavarian sister party Christian Social Union (CSU) as
well as the junior partner Free Democratic Party (FDP), says that
they would keep the current alliance.
</P>
<P>
On the other side, the leftist SPD is campaigning to come to
power in Bonn, after 16 years in opposition, in alliance with the
ecologist Greens.
</P>
<P>
If neither group could muster a parliamentary majority, as
recent polls indicated, the only option would be a so-called grand
coalition between the two biggest parties, the CDU and the SPD,
with the chancellor post going to the party with most votes.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder has said that he is willing to lead such a grand
coalition. But Kohl has said repeatedly that he wants no part of
that even when his CDU comes out ahead. That would open the door
to Kohl's preferred successor and the CDU's parliamentary leader,
Wolfgang Schaeuble to take over as chancellor.
</P>
<P>
Whoever might emerge as Germany's next chancellor, he will be
charged with the task to lead a country that will take over the
rotating presidencies of both the European Union (EU) and the
Group of Seven (G-7) western industrialized nations up from
January 1 next year and will join ten other EU countries to launch
the single European currency, the euro, on the same date.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980927.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Drug Approved for Advanced Breast Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 26 (Xinhua) -- A new drug named Herceptin
has been approved by the U.S. Food and Drug Administration for
the treatment of advanced breast cancer, according to a report from
Saturday's Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
Herceptin, made by California-based Genetech Inc. is the first
"monoclonal antibody" to be approved for the treatment of breast
cancer. It is transfused into the body and then binds to a protein
called HER2. The protein is found on the surface of some normal
cells and plays a role in regulating cell growth. Some tumors make
too much HER2. In clinical trials, the drug stunted growth of
those tumors.
</P>
<P>
Two clinical trials showed Herceptin's effectiveness. In one
study involving 469 patients, women she received the drug along
with chemotherapy had less rapid tumor growth, more tumors that
were reduced in size by 50 percent or more and a higher rate of
survival one year past treatment.
</P>
<P>
Forty-four percent of Herceptin users responded to treatment,
compared with 29 percent in the group receiving chemotherapy
alone; the one-year survival rate with Herceptin was 79 percent,
compared with 68 percent for chemotherapy alone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980927.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudan Complains About U.S. Strike Threats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Sudan has submitted a
memorandum to the U.N. Security Council to complain about the
U.S. recent threats of new strikes against Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of Sudanese Foreign Relations Ministry Hassan Abdin
told reporters Saturday that the memorandum called on the Security
Council to use its authority to prevent the U.S. from persistence in
violating the U.N. Charter.
</P>
<P>
"The recent U.S. threats are of a flagrant and open breach of the
U.N. Charter that bans use, or threats of using, force, thus
showing the seriousness of the situation and the ill-will of the
United States," he said.
</P>
<P>
The threats endangered regional security and raised concern
and panic among people of the region, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Sudan said it has received a memorandum from the U.S. permanent
representative to the U.N., which threatened that the U.S. will launch
new military strikes against Sudan in case any U.S. citizen or interest
worldwide falls under any attack.
</P>
<P>
Washington, which has repeatedly accused Sudan of practicing
and harboring terrorism, launched a missile attack on a
pharmaceutical factory last month in retaliation for the bombings on
August 7 of its embassies in Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Sudan also sent the memorandum to the Arab League, the
Organization of African Unity and the Non-Aligned Movement, Abdin
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980927.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-26 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2110GMT, September 26 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman Mahmoud Mohammadi
has been appointed as ambassador to Britain after Tehran and
London agreed to improve their relations, local daily Iran News
revealed on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Following the agreement reached between Iranian Foreign
Minister Kamal Kharrazi and his British counterpart Robin Cook in
New York on Thursday, Mohammadi will soon assume his post, the
daily said.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi is expected to help the two countries successfully
implement their new policies aimed at further expansion of
economic, cultural and political relations, said the daily.
</P>
<P>
The relations between Tehran and London were strained in 1989
after late Iranian supreme leader Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini
issued a religious decree against the life of British writer
Salman Rushdie, author of the controversial novel the Satanic
Verses. (BC-Iran-Britain-New Ambassador)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- The Iranian army and the Islamic Revolutionary
Guards Corps (IRGC) have concluded the Kowsar diving maneuvers in
the Persian Gulf waters, an Iranian military official announced
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Ali Razmjoo, an official from the maneuver headquarters, said
that the maneuvers started on Tuesday and ended on Friday after
"achieving all its pre-determined targets." (BC-Iran-Diving
Maneuvers)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Palestinian Legislative Council Speaker Ahmed Qureia
(Abu Ala) said Saturday the Palestinians are determined to declare
their independent state next May.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Egyptian Voice of Arabs radio
broadcast by telephone from Jerusalem, he described the
declaration of an independent Palestinian state as a "strategic"
and not a "tactical" issue.
</P>
<P>
"The Palestinian people will continue to strive to establish an
independent state with Jerusalem as its capital. Israel's threats
will not affect our will to announce our state," he added.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian National Authority President Yasser Arafat Friday
reiterated plans to declare a Palestinian state in next May
despite Israeli objections. (BC-Palestine-Statehood)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Arab League supports the declaration of the
Palestinian state on the grounds that it is the legitimate right
of the Palestinian people, Arab League (AL) Secretary General
Esmat Abdel Meguid said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"The U.N. Resolution 181 of 1947 which was Israel's birth
certificate also provided for setting up the Palestinian state,"
he added in an interview with the Egyptian Middle East News Agency.
</P>
<P>
"The declaration of the Palestinian state would come in
implementation of Oslo agreements and a reply to the Israeli
government's procrastination," he said. (BC-AL-Palestinian State)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- An Israeli Defense Ministry adviser has said that
Israel is developing a new defense and attack system that can
destroy missiles after they are launched from hostile neighbors,
Israel Radio reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The adviser, who spoke on condition of anonymity, did not
elaborate on the new system, only saying that the size of the
missile system is similar to that of the Arrow anti-missile
missile, the radio reported.
</P>
<P>
A more advanced system is needed as more advanced offensive
missiles are obtained by Israel's bitter rivals Iran, Iraq and
Syria, they said. (BC-Israel-New Missile)  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980927.0157 </DOCNO>
